<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sets-of-real-numbers"
xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>Sets of Real Numbers</title>

  <introduction>
  <p>
      We use <m>\R</m> to denote the set of real numbers. For
      <m>A,B\subseteq\R</m> and <m>c\in\R</m>, we define:
  </p>

  <ul>
      <li><m>A+B:=\{a+b : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>

      <li><m>AB:=\{ab : a\in A,\ b\in B\}</m></li>

      <li><m>cA:=\{c\}A=\{ca : a\in A\}</m></li>
    </ul>
  <p>
      In particular, <m>-A=\{-a : a\in A\}=\{a : -a\in A\}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Some subsets of <m>\R</m> that we will encounter frequently are:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The set of natural numbers <m>\N = \{1,2,3, \ldots\}</m></li>
    <li>The set of integers <m>\Z = \{0,\pm 1, \pm 2, \ldots\} = \N \cup
    \{0\} \cup -\N</m>.</li>
    <li>
    The set of rational numbers 
    <m>\Q = \{m/n \colon m, n \in \Z, n \neq 0\}</m>.
    </li>
  </ul>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-bounded-subsets">
    <title>Bounded Subsets of <m>\R</m></title>

    <p>
      A real number <m>b</m> is an <term>upper bound</term><idx><h>upper
      bound</h></idx><idx><h>bound</h><h>upper</h></idx> (resp. a <term>lower
      bound</term><idx><h>lower bound</h></idx>) of a set <m>A</m> of real
      numbers if <m>b \ge a</m> (resp. <m>b \le a</m>) for every <m>a \in
      A</m>. We write <m>\ub(A)</m> and <m>\lb(A)</m> for the sets of upper
      bounds and lower bounds of <m>A</m>, respectively. It is
      straightforward to check that <m>-\ub(A) = \lb(-A)</m>. In other words,
      <m>b</m> is an upper bound of <m>A</m> if and only if <m>-b</m> is a
      lower bound of <m>-A</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      A set <m>A\subseteq\R</m> is <term>bounded
      above</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>above</h></idx> (resp. <term>bounded
      below</term><idx><h>bounded</h><h>below</h></idx>) if it
      has an upper bound (resp. a lower bound). We say <m>A</m> is
      <term>bounded</term><idx><h>bounded</h></idx> if it is both bounded
      above and bounded below. A real-valued function is
      <term>bounded</term> (resp. bounded above, bounded below) if its range
      is bounded (resp. bounded above, bounded below).
      <idx><h>function</h><h>bounded</h></idx>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-bounded-subsets-examples">
      <statement>
	<ul>
	    <li>
		The interval <m>(0,1)</m> is bounded; for example, it is
		bounded above by <m>1</m> and bounded below by <m>0</m>.
	    </li>

	  <li>
	    The set <m>\{1/x \colon x \gt 0\}</m> is bounded below by
	    <m>0</m>, but it is not bounded above.
	  </li>

	  <li>
	  <m>\Z</m> is neither bounded below nor above.
	  </li>

	  <li>
	  Every finite set of real numbers is bounded.
	  </li>

	  <li>
	    Every real number is both an upper bound and a lower bound of
	    the empty set <m>\emptyset</m>.
	  </li>
	</ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      An upper bound of a set is also an upper bound of every subset of that
      set. Therefore, an intersection of sets that are bounded above is again
      bounded above. If <m>a</m> and <m>a'</m> are upper bounds of <m>A</m>
      and <m>A'</m>, respectively, then <m>\max\{a,a'\}</m> is an upper bound
      of <m>A \cup A'</m>. Thus, a finite union of sets bounded above is
      bounded above. Likewise, the family of subsets of <m>\R</m> that are
      bounded below (resp. bounded) is closed under arbitrary intersections
      and finite unions.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-bounded-iff-abs-bound">
      <statement>
        <p>
	  A set <m>A \subseteq \R</m> is bounded if and only if there exists
	  <m>M \ge 0</m> such that <m>A \subseteq [-M,M]</m>.
	</p>
      </statement> 

      <proof>
        <p>
          One implication is immediate: if <m>A \subseteq [-M,M]</m>, then
          <m>A</m> is bounded. For the other implication, suppose <m>A</m> is
          bounded. Then so is <m>-A</m>. Hence <m>A \cup -A</m> is bounded
          above, say by <m>M</m>. Then <m>|a| = \max\{a,-a\} \le M</m> for all
          <m>a\in A</m>, so <m>A \subseteq [-M,M]</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      A <term>supremum</term><idx><h>supremum</h></idx> of a set
      <m>A\subseteq\R</m>, denoted by <m>\sup A</m>, is the least upper bound
      of <m>A</m>. In other words, <m>u=\sup A</m> if <m>u</m> is an upper
      bound of <m>A</m> and <m>u\le b</m> for every upper bound <m>b</m>
      of <m>A</m>. Dually, an <term>infimum</term><idx><h>infimum</h></idx>
      of <m>A</m>, denoted by <m>\inf A</m>, is the greatest lower bound
      of <m>A</m>. In other words, <m>\ell=\inf A</m> if <m>\ell</m> is a
      lower bound of <m>A</m> and every lower bound of <m>A</m> is at most
      <m>\ell</m>. It is clear that <m>\sup A</m> (likewise <m>\inf A</m>),
      if it exists, is unique.
    </p>

    <p>
      A useful reformulation is: <m>u=\sup A</m> if and only if <m>u</m>
      is an upper bound of <m>A</m> and for every <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>
      there exists <m>a\in A</m> with <m>u-\varepsilon&lt;a\le u</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-inf-and-sup">
      <statement>
	<ul>
	   <li>
	      The set of upper bounds and the set of lower bounds of
	      <m>(0,1)</m> are <m>[1,\infty)</m> and <m>(-\infty,0]</m>,
	      respectively. Hence <m>\sup(0,1) = 1</m> and <m>\inf(0,1)
	      = 0</m>.	</li>

	   <li>
	     The set of upper bounds and the set of lower bounds of
	     <m>H:=\{1/x \colon x \lt 0\}</m> are <m>[0,\infty)</m> and the
	     empty set, respectively. Hence <m>\sup H = 0</m> and <m>\inf H</m>
	     does not exist.
	   </li>

	  <li>
	  <m>\Z</m> has neither a supremum nor an infimum.
	  </li>

		  <li>
		    The set of upper bounds and the set of lower bounds of
		    <m>\emptyset</m> are both <m>\R</m>. Conventionally, we write
		    <m>\sup \emptyset = -\infty</m> and
		    <m>\inf \emptyset = +\infty</m>. Note that neither
		    <m>\sup \emptyset</m> nor <m>\inf \emptyset</m> exists in
		    <m>\R</m>.
		  </li>
	</ul>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
